---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="DGNSS and SBAS">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container learn-container">

      <nav class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/learn">Learn</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <a href="/learn/positioning">Positioning</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <span>DGNSS and SBAS</span>
      </nav>

      <div class="article-header">
        <span class="badge">Positioning · Article 2 of 5</span>
        <h1>DGNSS and SBAS</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          Differential GNSS exploits a simple insight: two receivers close together experience nearly
          identical satellite clock, ephemeris and ionospheric errors. By computing corrections at a
          reference station with a known position and broadcasting them to a rover, errors that were
          metres can be reduced to decimetres — without any change to the rover hardware.
        </p>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>10 min read</span>
          <span>·</span>
          <span>Last updated March 2026</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="toc">
        <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#principle">The differential principle</a></li>
          <li><a href="#code-dgnss">Code-based DGNSS</a></li>
          <li><a href="#corrections">Correction types — PRC and RRC</a></li>
          <li><a href="#baseline-effect">The baseline effect</a></li>
          <li><a href="#sbas">SBAS — Satellite-Based Augmentation</a></li>
          <li><a href="#sbas-signals">SBAS signal structure</a></li>
          <li><a href="#accuracy">Accuracy comparison</a></li>
          <li><a href="#when-to-use">When to use DGNSS vs SBAS</a></li>
          <li><a href="#summary">Summary</a></li>
          <li><a href="#references">References</a></li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 1 -->
      <h2 id="principle">The differential principle</h2>
      <p>
        Consider a reference station at a precisely known position. It measures pseudoranges to visible
        satellites and compares them to the <em>expected</em> pseudoranges computed from its known
        position and the satellite ephemeris. The difference is the pseudorange correction (PRC) —
        the combined effect of all spatially correlated errors for that satellite:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">PRC_i = ρ_expected_i − ρ_measured_i</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          where ρ_expected_i = geometric range (from known position to satellite) + tropospheric delay
          (modelled) and ρ_measured_i = raw pseudorange measurement at the reference station.
          PRC_i therefore captures: satellite clock error + ephemeris error + ionospheric delay
          + any remaining tropospheric model error.
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The rover receives these corrections and applies them to its own pseudoranges before computing
        its position:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">ρ_corrected_i = ρ_rover_i + PRC_i</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          The corrected pseudorange has the spatially correlated errors largely removed.
          The rover then solves for position using ρ_corrected exactly as in standalone GNSS.
          Only errors that differ between reference and rover remain — primarily multipath
          and receiver noise (both local, uncorrelated).
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- DGNSS architecture diagram -->
      <div class="diagram-wrap">
        <div class="diagram-label">DGNSS architecture — reference station to rover</div>
        <svg viewBox="0 0 680 220" width="100%" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
          <defs>
            <marker id="arr6" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="8" refY="5" markerWidth="6" markerHeight="6" orient="auto-start-reverse">
              <path d="M2 1L8 5L2 9" fill="none" stroke="context-stroke" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
            </marker>
          </defs>
          <!-- Satellites -->
          <circle cx="200" cy="30" r="8" fill="var(--accent)" opacity="0.8"/>
          <circle cx="340" cy="20" r="8" fill="var(--accent)" opacity="0.8"/>
          <circle cx="480" cy="30" r="8" fill="var(--accent)" opacity="0.8"/>
          <text x="340" y="10" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--sans)">GNSS satellites</text>

          <!-- Reference station -->
          <rect x="60" y="130" width="130" height="60" rx="8" fill="none" stroke="var(--accent2)" stroke-width="1"/>
          <text x="125" y="152" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" fill="var(--accent2)" font-family="var(--sans)" font-weight="500">Reference station</text>
          <text x="125" y="168" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--sans)">Known position</text>
          <text x="125" y="182" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--sans)">Computes PRCs</text>

          <!-- Rover -->
          <rect x="490" y="130" width="130" height="60" rx="8" fill="none" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1"/>
          <text x="555" y="152" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" fill="var(--accent)" font-family="var(--sans)" font-weight="500">Rover</text>
          <text x="555" y="168" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--sans)">Unknown position</text>
          <text x="555" y="182" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--sans)">Applies PRCs</text>

          <!-- Correction data link -->
          <line x1="192" y1="158" x2="490" y2="158" stroke="var(--text3)" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="5 3" marker-end="url(#arr6)"/>
          <text x="341" y="148" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--sans)">Corrections (PRC, RRC)</text>
          <text x="341" y="175" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">Radio · NTRIP · SBAS · 4G</text>

          <!-- Signal lines from satellites -->
          <line x1="200" y1="38" x2="125" y2="130" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="0.8" stroke-dasharray="3 3" opacity="0.5" marker-end="url(#arr6)"/>
          <line x1="340" y1="28" x2="250" y2="130" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="0.8" stroke-dasharray="3 3" opacity="0.5" marker-end="url(#arr6)"/>
          <line x1="340" y1="28" x2="490" y2="130" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="0.8" stroke-dasharray="3 3" opacity="0.5" marker-end="url(#arr6)"/>
          <line x1="480" y1="38" x2="555" y2="130" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="0.8" stroke-dasharray="3 3" opacity="0.5" marker-end="url(#arr6)"/>
        </svg>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 2 -->
      <h2 id="code-dgnss">Code-based DGNSS</h2>
      <p>
        The simplest form of differential GNSS works on code pseudoranges — giving accuracy of
        0.5–3 m. This is what most maritime, aviation and consumer differential systems provide.
      </p>
      <p>
        The reference station broadcasts corrections in real time via a data link — historically
        an FM radio subcarrier or dedicated marine radio beacon, today typically via NTRIP over
        4G/LTE. The rover receives the corrections and applies them before computing position.
      </p>
      <p>
        The standard data format for DGNSS corrections is <strong>RTCM SC-104</strong>. Message
        types 1 and 9 carry pseudorange corrections; message type 3 carries reference station
        coordinates. See the <a href="/learn/protocols/rtcm">RTCM article</a> for protocol details.
      </p>

      <!-- SECTION 3 -->
      <h2 id="corrections">Correction types — PRC and RRC</h2>
      <p>
        A pseudorange correction is only accurate at the moment it was computed. Because satellites
        move, the geometric range changes continuously — and so does the error. To allow the rover
        to extrapolate corrections forward in time, DGNSS broadcasts two values per satellite:
      </p>

      <div class="correction-grid">
        <div class="correction-card">
          <div class="corr-name">PRC — Pseudorange Correction</div>
          <div class="corr-formula">PRC(t₀) = ρ_expected − ρ_measured</div>
          <div class="corr-desc">
            The correction valid at reference time t₀. Captures all systematic errors at that instant.
            Units: metres. One value per satellite.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="correction-card">
          <div class="corr-name">RRC — Range Rate Correction</div>
          <div class="corr-formula">RRC = dPRC/dt</div>
          <div class="corr-desc">
            The rate of change of the correction in m/s. Allows the rover to compute an updated
            correction at time t: PRC(t) = PRC(t₀) + RRC × (t − t₀).
            Typically &lt;0.1 m/s. Latency correction is critical for moving rovers.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-warn">
        <div class="callout-icon">⚠️</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Correction latency matters:</strong> If corrections are 5 seconds old and the
          satellite clock error is drifting at 0.05 m/s, the uncorrected drift is 0.25 m.
          The RRC mitigates this but is itself an estimate. For code DGNSS, correction latencies
          up to ~30 s are acceptable. For RTK carrier-phase, latency of more than a few seconds
          degrades performance significantly.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 4 -->
      <h2 id="baseline-effect">The baseline effect</h2>
      <p>
        Differential corrections work because nearby receivers share the same errors. But as the
        distance between reference and rover increases — the <strong>baseline length</strong> —
        errors become less correlated and the corrections become less effective.
      </p>

      <div class="baseline-table">
        <div class="baseline-row baseline-header">
          <span>Baseline</span>
          <span>Iono correction</span>
          <span>Residual iono error</span>
          <span>Typical accuracy</span>
        </div>
        <div class="baseline-row">
          <span>&lt;10 km</span>
          <span class="good">~99% effective</span>
          <span>&lt;0.1 m</span>
          <span class="good">0.3 – 0.5 m</span>
        </div>
        <div class="baseline-row">
          <span>10 – 50 km</span>
          <span class="ok">~95% effective</span>
          <span>0.1 – 0.3 m</span>
          <span class="ok">0.5 – 1.0 m</span>
        </div>
        <div class="baseline-row">
          <span>50 – 200 km</span>
          <span class="warn">~80% effective</span>
          <span>0.3 – 1.0 m</span>
          <span class="warn">1.0 – 2.0 m</span>
        </div>
        <div class="baseline-row">
          <span>&gt;500 km</span>
          <span class="bad">~50% effective</span>
          <span>&gt;1.5 m</span>
          <span class="bad">2.0 – 5.0 m</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        This is why maritime radio beacon DGNSS (broadcast from shore stations, usable up to
        ~300 km) gives ~1–3 m accuracy rather than the &lt;0.5 m achievable with a local base station.
        SBAS systems address this by modelling the ionosphere spatially — see below.
      </p>

      <!-- SECTION 5 -->
      <h2 id="sbas">SBAS — Satellite-Based Augmentation</h2>
      <p>
        Satellite-Based Augmentation Systems (SBAS) are regional infrastructure systems that broadcast
        DGNSS corrections and integrity information via geostationary satellites. They differ from
        ground-based DGNSS in three important ways:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Wide-area coverage:</strong> A single SBAS covers an entire continent using a network of ground reference stations.</li>
        <li><strong>Spatial ionospheric model:</strong> Rather than a single PRC per satellite, SBAS broadcasts an ionospheric grid with delay estimates at each grid point, enabling better corrections over large areas.</li>
        <li><strong>Integrity monitoring:</strong> SBAS provides guaranteed bounds on position error — if the system cannot guarantee the stated accuracy, it broadcasts an alert. This is why SBAS is approved for aviation navigation (APV-I and APV-II approaches).</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="sbas-systems">
        <div class="sbas-item">
          <div class="sbas-name">WAAS</div>
          <div class="sbas-region">North America</div>
          <div class="sbas-op">FAA</div>
        </div>
        <div class="sbas-item">
          <div class="sbas-name">EGNOS</div>
          <div class="sbas-region">Europe</div>
          <div class="sbas-op">EUSPA</div>
        </div>
        <div class="sbas-item">
          <div class="sbas-name">MSAS</div>
          <div class="sbas-region">Japan</div>
          <div class="sbas-op">JCAB</div>
        </div>
        <div class="sbas-item">
          <div class="sbas-name">GAGAN</div>
          <div class="sbas-region">India</div>
          <div class="sbas-op">AAI / ISRO</div>
        </div>
        <div class="sbas-item">
          <div class="sbas-name">SDCM</div>
          <div class="sbas-region">Russia</div>
          <div class="sbas-op">Roscosmos</div>
        </div>
        <div class="sbas-item">
          <div class="sbas-name">BDSBAS</div>
          <div class="sbas-region">China</div>
          <div class="sbas-op">CSNO</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 6 -->
      <h2 id="sbas-signals">SBAS signal structure</h2>
      <p>
        SBAS satellites broadcast on GPS L1 (1575.42 MHz) using the same BPSK modulation and
        1.023 Mcps chip rate as GPS C/A code. This means any GPS receiver can receive SBAS
        signals without hardware changes — only software needs updating to decode and apply
        the corrections.
      </p>
      <p>
        SBAS messages are 250 bits long, transmitted at 250 bps (one message per second).
        Each message type carries different correction data:
      </p>

      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Message type</th>
              <th>Content</th>
              <th>Update rate</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>MT 1</strong></td>
              <td>PRN mask — which satellites are being corrected</td>
              <td>As needed</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>MT 2–5</strong></td>
              <td>Fast corrections — pseudorange corrections for each satellite</td>
              <td>1 – 6 s</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>MT 6</strong></td>
              <td>Integrity information — UDRE bounds on fast corrections</td>
              <td>1 s</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>MT 7</strong></td>
              <td>Fast correction degradation factors</td>
              <td>120 s</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>MT 10</strong></td>
              <td>Degradation parameters for ranging function</td>
              <td>120 s</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>MT 18</strong></td>
              <td>Ionospheric grid point mask</td>
              <td>As needed</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>MT 24–25</strong></td>
              <td>Slow (long-term) satellite orbit and clock corrections</td>
              <td>120 s</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>MT 26</strong></td>
              <td>Ionospheric delay corrections at each grid point</td>
              <td>300 s</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>MT 28</strong></td>
              <td>Clock-ephemeris covariance matrix</td>
              <td>120 s</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">✈️</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Aviation use:</strong> SBAS enables <strong>APV-I</strong> (Approach with Vertical
          Guidance) and <strong>APV-II</strong> approaches at airports — reducing minimum descent
          altitudes to 250 ft and 200 ft respectively. This provides precision approach capability
          at thousands of airports that lack ILS. WAAS now supports LPV approaches at over
          4,000 US airports.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 7 -->
      <h2 id="accuracy">Accuracy comparison</h2>

      <div class="accuracy-grid">
        <div class="accuracy-card">
          <div class="acc-method">Standalone (L1)</div>
          <div class="acc-h">3 – 5 m</div>
          <div class="acc-label">Horizontal (95%)</div>
          <div class="acc-bar"><div class="acc-fill" style="width:90%; background:rgba(255,71,87,0.5);"></div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="accuracy-card">
          <div class="acc-method">Standalone (L1+L5)</div>
          <div class="acc-h">1 – 2 m</div>
          <div class="acc-label">Horizontal (95%)</div>
          <div class="acc-bar"><div class="acc-fill" style="width:55%; background:rgba(240,165,0,0.5);"></div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="accuracy-card">
          <div class="acc-method">SBAS (WAAS/EGNOS)</div>
          <div class="acc-h">0.5 – 1.5 m</div>
          <div class="acc-label">Horizontal (95%)</div>
          <div class="acc-bar"><div class="acc-fill" style="width:35%; background:rgba(251,191,36,0.5);"></div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="accuracy-card">
          <div class="acc-method">Local DGNSS (&lt;50 km)</div>
          <div class="acc-h">0.3 – 1.0 m</div>
          <div class="acc-label">Horizontal (95%)</div>
          <div class="acc-bar"><div class="acc-fill" style="width:22%; background:rgba(0,212,170,0.5);"></div></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 8 -->
      <h2 id="when-to-use">When to use DGNSS vs SBAS</h2>

      <div class="compare-grid">
        <div class="compare-card">
          <div class="compare-header" style="color:var(--accent2);border-bottom-color:rgba(0,153,255,0.2);background:rgba(0,153,255,0.05);">
            Local DGNSS — use when:
          </div>
          <div class="compare-body">
            <ul>
              <li>Sub-metre accuracy required over a defined work area</li>
              <li>Reference station available within 50 km</li>
              <li>Network RTK infrastructure available (CORS network)</li>
              <li>Real-time operation required (not post-processing)</li>
              <li>Budget for NTRIP subscription or own base station</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="compare-example">
              <strong>Example:</strong> Agricultural guidance, utility locating,
              topographic survey (moderate accuracy), port navigation.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="compare-card">
          <div class="compare-header" style="color:#fbbf24;border-bottom-color:rgba(251,191,36,0.2);background:rgba(251,191,36,0.05);">
            SBAS — use when:
          </div>
          <div class="compare-body">
            <ul>
              <li>Wide-area operation with no fixed infrastructure</li>
              <li>Free corrections acceptable (0.5–1.5 m)</li>
              <li>Aviation approach guidance required</li>
              <li>Integrity guarantee required (SBAS provides UDRE bounds)</li>
              <li>Receiver already supports SBAS (virtually all modern GPS receivers)</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="compare-example">
              <strong>Example:</strong> Aviation (APV approaches), maritime navigation,
              recreational use, road transport where &lt;1 m is sufficient.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 9 - SUMMARY -->
      <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
      <div class="summary-grid">
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📡</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Spatial correlation</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Nearby receivers share satellite clock, ephemeris and ionospheric errors. Differencing at a reference station removes these — leaving only local errors (multipath, noise).</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📏</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Baseline degrades corrections</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Ionospheric correlation decays with distance. Beyond 100 km, DGNSS corrections become less effective. SBAS models this spatially with an ionospheric grid.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🛰️</div>
          <div class="summary-title">SBAS is free and wide-area</div>
          <div class="summary-body">SBAS broadcasts via GEO satellites on GPS L1. Any GPS receiver can use it at no cost. Provides 0.5–1.5 m horizontal and integrity bounds for aviation.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📊</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Code DGNSS ceiling</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Even with perfect corrections, code DGNSS is limited by multipath (~1 m) and receiver noise (~0.3 m). Getting below 0.1 m requires carrier phase — that is RTK.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="nav-footer">
        <a href="/learn/positioning/standalone-gnss" class="nav-prev">← Standalone GNSS</a>
        <a href="/learn/positioning/rtk" class="nav-next">RTK →</a>
      </div>

      <div class="references" id="references">
        <h3>References and further reading</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>RTCM SC-104 Special Committee 104. RTCM Standard 10402.3 — Differential GNSS Services. <a href="https://www.rtcm.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">rtcm.org →</a></li>
          <li>ICAO Annex 10, Volume I — Radio Navigation Aids. Chapter 3 (SBAS standards).</li>
          <li>Kaplan, E. D. & Hegarty, C. J. (2017). <em>Understanding GPS/GNSS: Principles and Applications</em>, 3rd ed. Artech House. Chapter 8.</li>
          <li>FAA WAAS Performance Analysis. <a href="https://www.nstb.tc.faa.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">nstb.tc.faa.gov →</a></li>
          <li>EGNOS Service Definition Document. <a href="https://egnos-user-support.essp-sas.eu" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">egnos-user-support.essp-sas.eu →</a></li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

